  "local_port": 51802,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What should I do if I graduated from uni 11 years ago and had only found work two years after for only a few months?",
  "response": "If you graduated 11 years ago and have only had a few months of work experience since then, it\u2019s important to approach your situation strategically to rebuild your career path. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you get back on track:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Assess Your Current Situation**\n   - Reflect on why you haven\u2019t been employed for most of the past decade. Understanding the factors (e.g., personal circumstances, lack of opportunities, skills gap) will help you address them.\n   - Identify any skills, knowledge, or experiences you\u2019ve gained during this time, even if they\u2019re not from formal employment (e.g., volunteering, freelancing, caregiving, or self-study).\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Update Your Resume and LinkedIn Profile**\n   - Highlight any work experience, even if it was only for a few months. Focus on your achievements and skills developed during that time.\n   - Include non-traditional experiences (e.g., volunteering, online courses, personal projects) that demonstrate transferable skills like communication, teamwork, or problem-solving.\n   - Use a functional or hybrid resume format if you lack consistent work history. This emphasizes skills rather than chronological work experience.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Fill Skill Gaps**\n   - Identify the skills required for the jobs you\u2019re interested in. Use online platforms like Coursera, Udemy, LinkedIn Learning, or edX to gain relevant certifications or training.\n   - Consider short-term courses or bootcamps in high-demand fields (e.g., digital marketing, coding, data analysis, project management).\n   - If possible, volunteer or take on freelance projects to build practical experience.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Network Strategically**\n   - Reach out to former classmates, professors, or colleagues to let them know you\u2019re job-seeking. They may have leads or advice.\n   - Attend industry events, webinars, or meetups to connect with professionals in your field.\n   - Use LinkedIn to connect with people in your desired industry and engage with their content to build relationships.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Consider Entry-Level or Internship Roles**\n   - Be open to starting at an entry-level position or taking on internships (even unpaid, if feasible) to gain experience and build your resume.\n   - Look for roles in growing industries or companies that are more open to hiring candidates with non-linear career paths.\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Address the Employment Gap**\n   - Prepare a clear, honest explanation for your employment gap. Focus on what you\u2019ve been doing to stay productive and improve your skills (e.g., \u201cI took time off for personal reasons but have been actively upskilling and preparing to re-enter the workforce.\u201d).\n   - Turn your gap into a positive by highlighting how your experiences have prepared you for the role.\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Tailor Your Job Applications**\n   - Customize your resume and cover letter for each job application, emphasizing how your skills and experiences align with the role.\n   - Research companies and roles thoroughly to demonstrate genuine interest during interviews.\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Build Confidence**\n   - Practice answering common interview questions, especially those about your employment gap.\n   - Focus on your strengths and the value you bring to an employer, rather than dwelling on past challenges.\n\n---\n\n### 9. **Consider Alternative Career Paths**\n   - Explore careers that value transferable skills or don\u2019t require extensive formal experience (e.g., sales, customer service, administrative roles).\n   - Look into industries with high demand for talent, such as technology, healthcare, or trades.\n\n---\n\n### 10. **Seek Support**\n   - Work with a career coach or counselor to develop a tailored plan for re-entering the workforce.\n   - Consider joining job-seeker support groups or online communities for advice and encouragement.\n\n---\n\n### 11. **Stay Persistent and Positive**\n   - Re-entering the workforce after a long gap can take time, but consistency and a proactive approach will pay off.\n   - Celebrate small wins, like landing an interview or completing a course, to stay motivated.\n\n---\n\nBy taking these steps, you can gradually rebuild your career and find opportunities that align with your current goals and circumstances.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
